arch:property.oc:show_val: Locus 90 is the raised floor to the west of the threshold (Locus 89) between the southwest and northwest semicircular features in the “entrance room.” This floor disappears into the balk, with only three rows of it visible. It is made of small rectangular sandstone pavers, somewhat loosely laid with some snecking stones used against the threshold. The stones are basically uniform in size, though those at the north near Loci 98 and 108 are more roughly shaped. As the “entrance room” and the “frigidarium” are so symmetrical, it is likely that there is (or was) a similar feature to the “frigidarium” to the west of the current extent of the trench. The poor quality of this locus, especially compared to the finer floor of the “hypocaust room,” suggests that this raised floor may be a later addition, blocking and covering a feature that mirrored the pool to the east. This of course is a hypothetical interpretation, which could only be validated by further excavation to the west. Following this interpretation, Locus 90 will be phased to the period of reconfiguration of the bath complex (Stage 4).

Phase X: Site abandonment after major collapse dating to the Byzantine period from the CE 4th to 5th c. New drainage systems are installed including that associated with the newly built west precinct wall.
2.60 m north south -by- 0.90 m east west.
Raised floor between the southwest and northwest semicircular features, west of the west threshold (Locus 89)
